{"title_page": "Oroxylum indicum", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Oroxylum indicum Blanco1.219.png\n|image_caption = Plate from book ''Flora de Filipinas'', Gran edicion, Atlas I. by [[Francisco Manuel Blanco]], 1880-1883? where name is ''Bignonia quadripinnata'', Blanco.\n|display_parents = 2\n|genus = Oroxylum\n|parent_authority = Vent.\n|species = indicum\n|authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]) [[George Bentham|Benth.]] ex [[Wilhelm Sulpiz Kurz|Kurz]]\n|synonyms =\n* ''Arthrophyllum ceylanicum'' Miq.\t\n* ''Arthrophyllum reticulatum'' Blume ex Miq.\t\n* ''Bignonia indica'' L.\n* ''Bignonia lugubris'' Salisb.\n* ''Bignonia pentandra'' Lour.\n* ''Bignonia quadripinnata'' Blanco\n* ''Bignonia tripinnata'' Noronha\n* ''Bignonia tuberculata'' Roxb. ex DC.\n* ''Calosanthes indica'' (L.) Blume\n* ''Hippoxylon indica'' (L.) Raf.\n* ''Oroxylum flavum'' Rehder\n* ''Oroxylum indicum'' Vent. nom. inval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do;jsessionid=DC488BC0FF8BF223E9379C8EDFB111A9?id=60442729-2&back_page=%2Fipni%2FeditAdvPlantNameSearch.do%3Bjsessionid%3DDC488BC0FF8BF223E9379C8EDFB111A9%3Ffind_infragenus%3D%26find_isAPNIRecord%3Dtrue%26find_geoUnit%3D%26find_includePublicationAuthors%3Dtrue%26find_addedSince%3D%26find_family%3D%26find_genus%3Doroxylum%26find_sortByFamily%3Dtrue%26find_isGCIRecord%3Dtrue%26find_infrafamily%3D%26find_rankToReturn%3Dall%26find_publicationTitle%3D%26find_authorAbbrev%3D%26find_infraspecies%3D%26find_includeBasionymAuthors%3Dtrue%26find_modifiedSince%3D%26find_isIKRecord%3Dtrue%26find_species%3Dindicum%26output_format%3Dnormal|title=The International Plant Names Index}}</ref>\n* ''Spathodea indica'' (L.) Pers.\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>{{ThePlantList | id = kew-317739 | taxon = Oroxylum indicum | authority = (L.) Kurz | accessdate = 31 Mar 2016 }}</ref>\n|}}\n\n'''''Oroxylum indicum''''' is a species of [[flowering plant]] belonging to the [[monotypic]] genus '''''Oroxylum''''' and the family [[Bignoniaceae]], are commonly called '''midnight horror''',<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref> '''oroxylum''',<ref name=GRIN/> '''Indian trumpet flower''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecoport.org/ep?Plant=8133|title=Ecoport}}</ref> '''broken bones''',<ref name=\"bones\">{{cite web|title=Broken bones tree|url=http://www.flowersofindia.net/catalog/slides/Broken%20Bones%20Tree.html|publisher=Flowers of India|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> '''Indian caper''', or '''tree of Damocles'''.<ref name=\"ijps\">{{cite journal|pmc=3425058|year=2011|last2=Singh|first2=V|last3=Chaudhary|first3=A. K|title=A Review on the Taxonomy, Ethnobotany, Chemistry and Pharmacology of Oroxylum indicum Vent|journal=Indian Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences|volume=73|issue=5|pages=483\u2013490|doi=10.4103/0250-474X.98981|last1=Chaudhary|first1=AK|pmid=22923859}}</ref> It can reach a height of {{convert|18|m|ft}}. Various segments of the tree are used in [[traditional medicine]].<ref name=ijps/>\n\n==Description==\nThe large leaf stalks wither and fall off the tree and collect near the base of the trunk, appearing to look like a pile of broken limb bones. The [[pinnate]] leaves are approximately {{convert|1|m|ft}} in length and comparably wide,<ref name=bones/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/read.cfm?NewsID=881|title=The Midnight Horror Tree| last=Phillipps| first=Anthea| date=22 April 2012 |accessdate= 5 September 2012}}</ref> borne on [[petiole (botany)|petiole]]s or stalks up to {{convert|2|m|ft}} in length, making this the largest of all [[dicot]] tree leaves, which are quadripinnate (leaflets display four orders of branching).<ref>{{cite book | last= Corner | first= Prof. E.J.H. |date= 1952  | title= Wayside Trees of Malaya | location= Singapore | publisher= Govt. Printing Office | volume= 1 | page= 166 }}</ref>\n\nThe tree is a night-bloomer and flowers are adapted to natural [[Chiropterophily|pollination by bats]].<ref name=bones/> They form enormous seed pods &ndash; the fruits &ndash; are up to {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} long that hang down from bare branches, resembling [[sword]]s.<ref name=bones/><ref>{{cite book |vauthors=Barwick M, van der Schans A| date= 2004 |title= Tropical and Subtropical Trees - An Encyclopedia | location= Portland | publisher= Timber Press | page= 304 }}</ref> The long fruits curve downward and resemble the wings of a large bird or dangling sickles or swords in the night, giving the name \"tree of [[Damocles]]\".<ref name=ijps/> The seeds are round with papery wings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=620&taxon_id=200021430|title=''Oroxylum indicum''|publisher=Dinghushan Plant Checklist, Chinese Academy of Science|website=eFloras.org}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n''Ooroxylum indicum'' is native to the [[Indian subcontinent]], the [[Himalayas|Himalayan foothills]] with a part extending to [[Bhutan]] and southern China, [[Indochina]] and the [[Malesia]] regions.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} In [[Vietnam]], the tree is called ''n\u00fac n\u00e1c'' (sometimes ''s\u00f2 \u0111o''), and specimens can be found in [[Cat Tien National Park]].\n\nIt is visible in the forest biome of [[Manas National Park]] in Assam, India. It is found, raised and planted in large number in the forest areas of the [[Banswara district|Banswara]] district in the state of Rajasthan in India. It is reported in the list of [[Rare, Endangered and Threatened (RET) plants of Kerala|rare, endangered and threatened plants of Kerala]] (South India). It is also found in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"Theobald\">Theobald, W.L. (1981). ''Bignoniace.'' In: Dassanayake, M.D. and Fosberg, F.R. (Eds.). ''A Revised Handbook to the Flora of Ceylon.'' Amerind Publishing Co. Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi.</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\n''Oroxylum indicum'' lives in relationship with the actinomycete ''[[Pseudonocardia oroxyli]]'' present in the soil surrounding the roots.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pseudonocardia oroxyli sp. nov., a novel actinomycete isolated from surface-sterilized Oroxylum indicum root|first1=Qiang|last1=Gu|first2=Hongli|last2=Luo|first3=Wen|last3=Zheng|first4=Zhiheng|last4=Liu|first5=Ying|last5=Huang|date=1 September 2006|publisher=|journal=Int. J. Syst. Evol. Microbiol.|volume=56|issue=Pt 9|pages=2193\u20132197|doi=10.1099/ijs.0.64385-0|pmid=16957120}}</ref> ''[[Septobasidium bogoriense]]'' is a [[fungus|fungal]] species responsible for [[velvet blight]] in ''O. indicum''.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Phytochemistry==\nVarious segments of ''O. indicum'', including leaves, root bark, [[duramen|heartwood]], and seeds, contain diverse [[phytochemical]]s, such as [[prunetin]], [[sitosterol]], [[oroxindin]], [[oroxylin-A]], [[biochanin-A]], [[ellagic acid]], [[tetuin]], [[anthraquinone]], and [[emodin]].<ref name=ijps/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rsc.org/publishing/journals/JR/article.asp?doi=jr9360000591|title=131. The constitution of oroxylin-A, a yellow colouring matter from the root-bark of Oroxylum indicum, vent|first1=R. C.|last1=Shah|first2=C. R.|last2=Mehta|first3=T. S.|last3=Wheeler|date=1 January 1936|publisher=|journal=J. Chem. Soc.|pages=591|doi=10.1039/JR9360000591}}</ref> Several of the compounds are under preliminary research to identify their potential biological properties.<ref name=ijps/>\n\n==Uses==\nThe tree is often grown as an [[ornamental plant]] for its strange appearance. Materials used include the wood, [[tannin]]s and dyestuffs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Neill |first1=Alexander |display-authors=etal |date=2017-03-29 |title=Integrating ethnobiological knowledge into biodiversity conservation in the Eastern Himalayas |url=https://ethnobiomed.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |journal=Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine |volume=13 |issue=21 |doi=10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |access-date=2017-05-11 |pmc=5372287 |pmid=28356115}}</ref>\n\n===In marriage rituals=== \nThe plant is used by the [[Kirati people|Kirat]], [[Sunwar people|Sunuwar]], [[Rai people|Rai]], [[Limbu people|Limbu]], [[Yakha]], Tamang in Nepal, the [[Thai People|Thai]] in Thailand and the [[Lao People|Lao]] in Laos.\n\nIn the Himalayas, people hang [[Mobile (sculpture)|sculptures]] or [[garland]]s made from ''O. indicum'' (Skr. shyonaka) seeds from the roof of their homes in belief they provide protection.<ref>{{cite book|title=Trees and Shrubs of Nepal and the Himalayas; page 200|authors=Storrs  A, Storrs J|publisher=Pilgrims Books House|date=1990|isbn=9747315432}}</ref>\n\n===As food===\nIt is a [[List of plants with edible leaves|plant with edible leaves]] and stems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epic.kew.org/searchepic/detailquery.do?requiredPage=1&scientificName=oroxylum%20indicum&datasources=ipni&datasources=mc&datasources=kr&datasources=libcat&datasources=pmb&datasources=ebbd&datasources=ecbot&datasources=livcoll&datasources=herbcat&datasources=sid&datasources=sepasal&datasources=efz&categories=names&categories=bibl&categories=colln&categories=taxon&categories=flora&categories=misc&detailDatasource=sepasal|title=ePIC - Detailed results from SEPASAL for oroxylum indicum|publisher=}}</ref> The large young pods, known as ''Lin mai'' or ''Lin fa'' in [[Loei]], are eaten especially in [[Thailand]] and [[Laos]]. They are first grilled over charcoal fire and then the bitter inner pulp is usually scraped and eaten along with [[larb|lap]].<ref>[http://www.thaifoodcook.info/headlines/thai-dishes-central-part-and-south/ Thai Dishes, Central Part And South] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330182049/http://www.thaifoodcook.info/headlines/thai-dishes-central-part-and-south/ |date=March 30, 2012 }}</ref> Known as karongkandai among the Bodos of north east India, its flowers and fruit are eaten as a bitter side dish with rice. It often prepared with fermented or dried fish and believed by them to have medicinal uses.\n\n===In traditional medicines===\n''Oroxylum indicum'' seeds are used in [[traditional medicine|traditional]] Indian [[Ayurveda|Ayurvedic]] and Chinese medicines.<ref name=ijps/> Root bark is one of the ingredients thought to be useful in compound formulations in Ayurveda and other folk remedies.<ref name=ijps/><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=3545239|year=2012|author1=Doshi|first1=K|title=Anti-inflammatory activity of root bark and stem bark of Shyonaka|journal=Journal of Ayurveda and Integrative Medicine|volume=3|issue=4|pages=194\u2013197|last2=Ilanchezhian|first2=R|last3=Acharya|first3=R|last4=Patel|first4=B. R.|last5=Ravishankar|first5=B|doi=10.4103/0975-9476.104434|pmid=23326090}}</ref><ref name=\"Jayaweera\">Jayaweera, D.M.A. (1981). ''Medicinal Plants (Indigenous and Exotic) Used in Ceylon. Part I (Acanthaceae \u2013 Burseraceae).'' National Science Council of Sri Lanka, Colombo.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Oroxylum indicum W3 IMG 3170.jpg|Flowers\nFile:Oroxylum indicum W IMG 3169.jpg|Leaves\nFile:Oroxylum indicum W2 IMG 3171.jpg|Fruit\nFile:Oroxylum indicum250.jpg|The large ''Oroxylum indicum'' pods sold at a market in [[Bangkok]], Thailand\nFile:Oroxylum indicum.JPG|''Oroxylum indicum'' near [[Panchkhal]], [[Nepal]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Thai ingredients]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Taxonbar|from1=Q3245941|from2=Q7103907}}\n\n[[Category:Bignoniaceae]]\n[[Category:Plants used in Ayurveda]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional Chinese medicine]]\n[[Category:Decorative fruits and seeds]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Indian subcontinent]]\n[[Category:Trees of Indo-China]]\n[[Category:Trees of Malesia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n[[Category:Trees of Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Oroxylum indicum Blanco1.219.png\n|image_caption = Plate from book ''Flora de Filipinas'', Gran edicion, Atlas I. by [[Francisco Manuel Blanco]], 1880-1883? where name is ''Bignonia quadripinnata'', Blanco.\n|display_parents = 2\n|genus = Oroxylum\n|parent_authority = Vent.\n|species = indicum\n|authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]) [[George Bentham|Benth.]] ex [[Wilhelm Sulpiz Kurz|Kurz]]\n|synonyms =\n* ''Arthrophyllum ceylanicum'' Miq.\t\n* ''Arthrophyllum reticulatum'' Blume ex Miq.\t\n* ''Bignonia indica'' L.\n* ''Bignonia lugubris'' Salisb.\n* ''Bignonia pentandra'' Lour.\n* ''Bignonia quadripinnata'' Blanco\n* ''Bignonia tripinnata'' Noronha\n* ''Bignonia tuberculata'' Roxb. ex DC.\n* ''Calosanthes indica'' (L.) Blume\n* ''Hippoxylon indica'' (L.) Raf.\n* ''Oroxylum flavum'' Rehder\n* ''Oroxylum indicum'' Vent. nom. inval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do;jsessionid=DC488BC0FF8BF223E9379C8EDFB111A9?id=60442729-2&back_page=%2Fipni%2FeditAdvPlantNameSearch.do%3Bjsessionid%3DDC488BC0FF8BF223E9379C8EDFB111A9%3Ffind_infragenus%3D%26find_isAPNIRecord%3Dtrue%26find_geoUnit%3D%26find_includePublicationAuthors%3Dtrue%26find_addedSince%3D%26find_family%3D%26find_genus%3Doroxylum%26find_sortByFamily%3Dtrue%26find_isGCIRecord%3Dtrue%26find_infrafamily%3D%26find_rankToReturn%3Dall%26find_publicationTitle%3D%26find_authorAbbrev%3D%26find_infraspecies%3D%26find_includeBasionymAuthors%3Dtrue%26find_modifiedSince%3D%26find_isIKRecord%3Dtrue%26find_species%3Dindicum%26output_format%3Dnormal|title=The International Plant Names Index}}</ref>\n* ''Spathodea indica'' (L.) Pers.\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>{{ThePlantList | id = kew-317739 | taxon = Oroxylum indicum | authority = (L.) Kurz | accessdate = 31 Mar 2016 }}</ref>\n|}}\n\n'''''Oroxylum indicum''''' is a species of [[flowering plant]] belonging to the [[monotypic]] genus '''''Oroxylum''''' and the family [[Bignoniaceae]], are commonly called '''midnight horror''',<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN | accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref> '''oroxylum''',<ref name=GRIN/> '''Indian trumpet flower''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecoport.org/ep?Plant=8133|title=Ecoport}}</ref> '''broken bones''',<ref name=\"bones\">{{cite web|title=Broken bones tree|url=http://www.flowersofindia.net/catalog/slides/Broken%20Bones%20Tree.html|publisher=Flowers of India|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> '''Indian caper''', or '''tree of Damocles'''.<ref name=\"ijps\">{{cite journal|pmc=3425058|year=2011|last2=Singh|first2=V|last3=Chaudhary|first3=A. K|title=A Review on the Taxonomy, Ethnobotany, Chemistry and Pharmacology of Oroxylum indicum Vent|journal=Indian Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences|volume=73|issue=5|pages=483\u2013490|doi=10.4103/0250-474X.98981|last1=Chaudhary|first1=AK|pmid=22923859}}</ref> It can reach a height of {{convert|18|m|ft}}. Various segments of the tree are used in [[traditional medicine]].<ref name=ijps/>\n\n==Description==\nThe large leaf stalks wither and fall off the tree and collect near the base of the trunk, appearing to look like a pile of broken limb bones. The [[pinnate]] leaves are approximately {{convert|1|m|ft}} in length and comparably wide,<ref name=bones/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/read.cfm?NewsID=881|title=The Midnight Horror Tree| last=Phillipps| first=Anthea| date=22 April 2012 |accessdate= 5 September 2012}}</ref> borne on [[petiole (botany)|petiole]]s or stalks up to {{convert|2|m|ft}} in length, making this the largest of all [[dicot]] tree leaves, which are quadripinnate (leaflets display four orders of branching).<ref>{{cite book | last= Corner | first= Prof. E.J.H. |date= 1952  | title= Wayside Trees of Malaya | location= Singapore | publisher= Govt. Printing Office | volume= 1 | page= 166 }}</ref>\n\nThe tree is a night-bloomer and flowers are adapted to natural [[Chiropterophily|pollination by bats]].<ref name=bones/> They form enormous seed pods &ndash; the fruits &ndash; are up to {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} long that hang down from bare branches, resembling [[sword]]s.<ref name=bones/><ref>{{cite book |vauthors=Barwick M, van der Schans A| date= 2004 |title= Tropical and Subtropical Trees - An Encyclopedia | location= Portland | publisher= Timber Press | page= 304 }}</ref> The long fruits curve downward and resemble the wings of a large bird or dangling sickles or swords in the night, giving the name \"tree of [[Damocles]]\".<ref name=ijps/> The seeds are round with papery wings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=620&taxon_id=200021430|title=''Oroxylum indicum''|publisher=Dinghushan Plant Checklist, Chinese Academy of Science|website=eFloras.org}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n''Ooroxylum indicum'' is native to the [[Indian subcontinent]], the [[Himalayas|Himalayan foothills]] with a part extending to [[Bhutan]] and southern China, [[Indochina]] and the [[Malesia]] regions.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} In [[Vietnam]], the tree is called ''n\u00fac n\u00e1c'' (sometimes ''s\u00f2 \u0111o''), and specimens can be found in [[Cat Tien National Park]].\n\nIt is visible in the forest biome of [[Manas National Park]] in Assam, India. It is found, raised and planted in large number in the forest areas of the [[Banswara district|Banswara]] district in the state of Rajasthan in India. It is reported in the list of [[Rare, Endangered and Threatened (RET) plants of Kerala|rare, endangered and threatened plants of Kerala]] (South India). It is also found in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"Theobald\">Theobald, W.L. (1981). ''Bignoniace.'' In: Dassanayake, M.D. and Fosberg, F.R. (Eds.). ''A Revised Handbook to the Flora of Ceylon.'' Amerind Publishing Co. Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi.</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\n''Oroxylum indicum'' lives in relationship with the actinomycete ''[[Pseudonocardia oroxyli]]'' present in the soil surrounding the roots.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pseudonocardia oroxyli sp. nov., a novel actinomycete isolated from surface-sterilized Oroxylum indicum root|first1=Qiang|last1=Gu|first2=Hongli|last2=Luo|first3=Wen|last3=Zheng|first4=Zhiheng|last4=Liu|first5=Ying|last5=Huang|date=1 September 2006|publisher=|journal=Int. J. Syst. Evol. Microbiol.|volume=56|issue=Pt 9|pages=2193\u20132197|doi=10.1099/ijs.0.64385-0|pmid=16957120}}</ref> ''[[Septobasidium bogoriense]]'' is a [[fungus|fungal]] species responsible for [[velvet blight]] in ''O. indicum''.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Phytochemistry==\nVarious segments of ''O. indicum'', including leaves, root bark, [[duramen|heartwood]], and seeds, contain diverse [[phytochemical]]s, such as [[prunetin]], [[sitosterol]], [[oroxindin]], [[oroxylin-A]], [[biochanin-A]], [[ellagic acid]], [[tetuin]], [[anthraquinone]], and [[emodin]].<ref name=ijps/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rsc.org/publishing/journals/JR/article.asp?doi=jr9360000591|title=131. The constitution of oroxylin-A, a yellow colouring matter from the root-bark of Oroxylum indicum, vent|first1=R. C.|last1=Shah|first2=C. R.|last2=Mehta|first3=T. S.|last3=Wheeler|date=1 January 1936|publisher=|journal=J. Chem. Soc.|pages=591|doi=10.1039/JR9360000591}}</ref> Several of the compounds are under preliminary research to identify their potential biological properties.<ref name=ijps/>\n\n==Uses==\nThe tree is often grown as an [[ornamental plant]] for its strange appearance. Materials used include the wood, [[tannin]]s and dyestuffs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Neill |first1=Alexander |display-authors=etal |date=2017-03-29 |title=Integrating ethnobiological knowledge into biodiversity conservation in the Eastern Himalayas |url=https://ethnobiomed.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |journal=Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine |volume=13 |issue=21 |doi=10.1186/s13002-017-0148-9 |access-date=2017-05-11 |pmc=5372287 |pmid=28356115}}</ref>\n\n===In marriage rituals=== \nThe plant is used by the [[Kirati people|Kirat]], [[Sunwar people|Sunuwar]], [[Rai people|Rai]], [[Limbu people|Limbu]], [[Yakha]], Tamang in Nepal, the [[Thai People|Thai]] in Thailand and the [[Lao People|Lao]] in Laos.\n\nIn the Himalayas, people hang [[Mobile (sculpture)|sculptures]] or [[garland]]s made from ''O. indicum'' (Skr. shyonaka) seeds from the roof of their homes in belief they provide protection.<ref>{{cite book|title=Trees and Shrubs of Nepal and the Himalayas; page 200|authors=Storrs  A, Storrs J|publisher=Pilgrims Books House|date=1990|isbn=9747315432}}</ref>\n\n===As food===\nIt is a [[List of plants with edible leaves|plant with edible leaves]] and stems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epic.kew.org/searchepic/detailquery.do?requiredPage=1&scientificName=oroxylum%20indicum&datasources=ipni&datasources=mc&datasources=kr&datasources=libcat&datasources=pmb&datasources=ebbd&datasources=ecbot&datasources=livcoll&datasources=herbcat&datasources=sid&datasources=sepasal&datasources=efz&categories=names&categories=bibl&categories=colln&categories=taxon&categories=flora&categories=misc&detailDatasource=sepasal|title=ePIC - Detailed results from SEPASAL for oroxylum indicum|publisher=}}</ref> The large young pods, known as ''Lin mai'' or ''Lin fa'' in [[Loei]], are eaten especially in [[Thailand]] and [[Laos]]. They are first grilled over charcoal fire and then the bitter inner pulp is usually scraped and eaten along with [[larb|lap]].<ref>[http://www.thaifoodcook.info/headlines/thai-dishes-central-part-and-south/ Thai Dishes, Central Part And South] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330182049/http://www.thaifoodcook.info/headlines/thai-dishes-central-part-and-south/ |date=March 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===In traditional medicines===\n''Oroxylum indicum'' seeds are used in [[traditional medicine|traditional]] Indian [[Ayurveda|Ayurvedic]] and Chinese medicines.<ref name=ijps/> Root bark is one of the ingredients thought to be useful in compound formulations in Ayurveda and other folk remedies.<ref name=ijps/><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=3545239|year=2012|author1=Doshi|first1=K|title=Anti-inflammatory activity of root bark and stem bark of Shyonaka|journal=Journal of Ayurveda and Integrative Medicine|volume=3|issue=4|pages=194\u2013197|last2=Ilanchezhian|first2=R|last3=Acharya|first3=R|last4=Patel|first4=B. R.|last5=Ravishankar|first5=B|doi=10.4103/0975-9476.104434|pmid=23326090}}</ref><ref name=\"Jayaweera\">Jayaweera, D.M.A. (1981). ''Medicinal Plants (Indigenous and Exotic) Used in Ceylon. Part I (Acanthaceae \u2013 Burseraceae).'' National Science Council of Sri Lanka, Colombo.</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Oroxylum indicum W3 IMG 3170.jpg|Flowers\nFile:Oroxylum indicum W IMG 3169.jpg|Leaves\nFile:Oroxylum indicum W2 IMG 3171.jpg|Fruit\nFile:Oroxylum indicum250.jpg|The large ''Oroxylum indicum'' pods sold at a market in [[Bangkok]], Thailand\nFile:Oroxylum indicum.JPG|''Oroxylum indicum'' near [[Panchkhal]], [[Nepal]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Thai ingredients]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Taxonbar|from1=Q3245941|from2=Q7103907}}\n\n[[Category:Bignoniaceae]]\n[[Category:Plants used in Ayurveda]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional Chinese medicine]]\n[[Category:Decorative fruits and seeds]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Indian subcontinent]]\n[[Category:Trees of Indo-China]]\n[[Category:Trees of Malesia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n[[Category:Trees of Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "Manjitrupbikram", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added an additional food item", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oroxylum_indicum"}
{"title_page": "March 20", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}} Typically the [[March equinox]] falls on this date, marking the vernal point in the [[Northern Hemisphere]] and the autumnal point in the [[Southern Hemisphere]].\n\n==Events==\n* [[235]] &ndash; [[Maximinus Thrax]] is proclaimed emperor.\n* [[673]] &ndash; Emperor [[Emperor Tenmu|Tenmu]] of Japan assumes the [[Chrysanthemum Throne]] at the [[Asuka, Yamato#Imperial Palaces|Palace of Kiyomihara]] in [[Asuka, Yamato|Asuka]].\n*[[1206]] &ndash; [[Michael IV of Constantinople|Michael IV Autoreianos]] is appointed [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]].\n*[[1600]] &ndash; The [[Link\u00f6ping Bloodbath]] takes place on [[Maundy Thursday]] in [[Link\u00f6ping]], Sweden: five Swedish noblemen are [[public execution|publicly beheaded]] in the aftermath of the [[War against Sigismund]] (1598\u20131599).<ref>{{cite book|author=Serge\u012d Mikha\u012dlovich Solov\u02b9ev|title=History of Russia: The Reign of Tsar Fedor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8LJoAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Academic International Press|isbn=978-0-87569-243-2|page=187}}</ref>\n*[[1602]] &ndash; The [[Dutch East India Company]] is established.\n*[[1616]] &ndash; Sir [[Walter Raleigh]] is freed from the [[Tower of London]] after 13 years of imprisonment.\n*[[1760]] &ndash; The [[Great Boston Fire of 1760]] destroys 349 buildings.\n*[[1815]] &ndash; After escaping from [[Elba]], [[Napoleon]] enters Paris with a regular army of 140,000 and a volunteer force of around 200,000, beginning his \"[[Hundred Days]]\" rule.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; [[German revolutions of 1848\u201349]]: [[Monarch|King]] [[Ludwig I of Bavaria]] abdicates.\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]]'s ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'' is published.\n*[[1854]] &ndash; The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party of the United States]] is organized in [[Ripon, Wisconsin]], US.\n*[[1861]] &ndash; An [[1861 Mendoza earthquake|earthquake]] destroys [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]], [[Argentina]].\n*[[1883]] &ndash; The [[Paris Convention for the Protection of Industrial Property]] is signed.\n*[[1888]] &ndash; The premiere of the very first [[Romen Theatre#Forerunners of Romen Theatre|Romani language operetta]] is staged in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]].\n*[[1890]] &ndash; Prime Minister of the [[German Empire]] [[Otto von Bismarck]] is dismissed by [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Emperor Wilhelm II]].\n*[[1896]] &ndash; With the approval of [[Guangxu Emperor|Emperor Guangxu]], [[:zh:\u5927\u6e05\u90ae\u653f\u603b\u5c40|the Qing dynasty post office]] is opened, marking the beginning of a postal service in China. \n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Sung Chiao-jen]], a founder of the [[Kuomintang|Chinese Nationalist Party]], is wounded in an assassination attempt and dies 2 days later.\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Albert Einstein]] publishes his [[general relativity|general theory of relativity]].\n*[[1921]] &ndash; The [[Upper Silesia plebiscite]] was a [[plebiscite]] mandated by the [[Versailles Treaty]] to determine a section of the border between [[Weimar Germany]] and [[Poland]].\n*[[1922]] &ndash; The {{USS|Langley|CV-1|6}} is commissioned as the first [[United States Navy]] [[aircraft carrier]].\n*[[1923]] &ndash; The [[Arts Club of Chicago]] hosts the opening of [[Pablo Picasso]]'s first United States showing, entitled ''Original Drawings by Pablo Picasso'', becoming an early proponent of [[modern art]] in the United States.\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Reichsf\u00fchrer-SS]] [[Heinrich Himmler]] ordered the creation of [[Dachau concentration camp]] as [[Chief of Police]] of [[Munich]] and appointed [[Theodor Eicke]] as the camp commandant.\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[General]] [[Douglas MacArthur]], at [[Terowie, South Australia]], makes his famous speech regarding the [[Battle of the Philippines (1942)|fall of the Philippines]], in which he says: \"I came out of [[Bataan]] and I shall return\".\n*[[1948]] &ndash; With a [[American Federation of Musicians|Musicians Union]] ban lifted, the first telecasts of classical music in the United States, under [[Eugene Ormandy]] and [[Arturo Toscanini]], are given on [[CBS]] and [[NBC]].\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Fujiyoshida]], a city located in [[Yamanashi Prefecture]], Japan, in the center of the Japanese main island of [[Honsh\u016b]] is founded.\n*[[1952]] &ndash; The US Senate ratifies the [[Security Treaty Between the United States and Japan]].\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Tunisia]] gains independence from France.\n*[[1964]] &ndash; The [[wiktionary:Precursor|precursor]] of the [[European Space Agency]], ESRO ([[European Space Research Organisation]]) is established per an agreement signed on [[June 14]], [[1962]].\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[The Troubles]]: The first [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]] [[Donegall Street bombing|car bombing]] in [[Belfast]] kills seven people and injures 148 others in [[Northern Ireland]]. \n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Libby Riddles]] becomes the first woman to win the 1,135-mile [[Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race]].\n*  1985   &ndash; Canadian [[paraplegic]] athlete and [[humanitarian]] [[Rick Hansen]] begins his [[circumnavigation]] of the globe in a wheelchair in the name of [[spinal cord]] injury medical research.\n*[[1987]] &ndash; The [[Food and Drug Administration]] approves the anti-[[AIDS]] drug, [[Zidovudine|AZT]].\n*[[1988]] &ndash; [[Eritrean War of Independence]]: Having defeated the Nadew Command, the [[Eritrean People's Liberation Front]] enters the town of [[Afabet]], victoriously concluding the [[Battle of Afabet]].\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand Marcos]]'s widow, [[Imelda Marcos]], goes on trial for [[bribery]], [[embezzlement]], and [[racketeering]].\n*[[1993]] &ndash; The Troubles: A Provisional IRA bomb [[Warrington bomb attacks|kills two children]] in [[Warrington]], England. It leads to mass protests in both Britain and Ireland.\n*[[1995]] &ndash; The Japanese cult [[Aum Shinrikyo]] carries out a [[sarin gas attack on the Tokyo subway]], killing 13 and wounding over 6,200 people.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Legoland California]], the first [[Legoland]] outside of Europe, opens in [[Carlsbad, California]], US.\n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin]], a former [[Black Panther Party|Black Panther]] once known as [[H. Rap Brown]], is captured after murdering [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] sheriff's deputy Ricky Kinchen and critically wounding Deputy Aldranon English.\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[2003 invasion of Iraq|Invasion of Iraq]]: In the early hours of the morning, the United States and three other countries (the UK, Australia and Poland) begin military operations in [[Iraq]].\n*[[2006]] &ndash; Over 150 [[Chadian soldier]]s are killed in eastern [[Chad]] by members of the rebel [[United Front for Democratic Change|UFDC]]. The rebel movement sought to overthrow [[Head of state of Chad|Chadian president]] [[Idriss D\u00e9by]].\n*[[2012]] &ndash; At least 52 people are killed and more than 250 injured in a [[20 March 2012 Iraq attacks|wave of terror attacks]] across ten cities in [[Iraq]].\n*[[2014]] &ndash; Four suspected [[Taliban]] members [[2014 Kabul Serena Hotel attack|attack]] the [[Kabul Serena Hotel]], killing at least nine people.\n*[[2015]] &ndash; A [[Solar eclipse of March 20, 2015|Solar eclipse]], [[equinox]], and a [[supermoon]] all occur on the same day.\n\n==Births==\n*[[43 BC]] &ndash; [[Ovid]], Roman poet (d. 17)\n*[[1253]] &ndash; Magadu, renamed [[Wareru]], founder of Ramanya Kingdom, renamed Hanthawady Kingdom of Pegu (b. a commoner; d. on a Saturday in January 1307)\n*[[1319]] &ndash; [[Laurence Hastings, 1st Earl of Pembroke]] (d. 1348)\n*[[1469]] &ndash; [[Cecily of York]] (d. 1507)\n*[[1477]] &ndash; [[Jerome Emser]], German theologian and scholar (d. 1527)\n*[[1479]] &ndash; [[Ippolito d'Este]], Italian cardinal (d. 1520)\n*[[1502]] &ndash; [[Pierino Belli]], Italian soldier and jurist (d. 1575)\n*[[1532]] &ndash; [[Juan de Ribera]], Roman Catholic archbishop (d. 1611)\n*[[1612]] &ndash; [[Anne Bradstreet]], Puritan American poet (d. 1672)\n*[[1615]] &ndash; [[Dara Shikoh]], Indian prince (d. 1659)\n*[[1639]] &ndash; [[Ivan Mazepa]], Ukrainian diplomat, [[Hetmans of Ukrainians Cossacks|Hetman of Ukraine]] (d. 1709)\n*[[1725]] &ndash; [[Abdul Hamid I]], Ottoman sultan (d. 1789)\n*[[1737]] &ndash; [[Rama I]], Thai king (d. 1809)\n*[[1771]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Clauren]], German author (d. 1854)\n*[[1796]] &ndash; [[Edward Gibbon Wakefield]], English politician (d. 1862)\n*[[1799]] &ndash; [[Karl August Nicander]], Swedish poet and author (d. 1839)\n*[[1800]] &ndash; [[Braulio Carrillo Colina]], Costa Rican lawyer and politician, [[President of Costa Rica]] (d. 1845)\n*[[1805]] &ndash; [[Thomas Cooper (poet)|Thomas Cooper]], British poet (d. 1892)\n*[[1811]] &ndash; [[Napoleon II]], French emperor (d. 1832)\n*  1811   &ndash; [[George Caleb Bingham]], American painter and politician, [[State Treasurer of Missouri]] (d. 1879)\n*[[1821]] &ndash; [[Ned Buntline]], American journalist, author, and publisher (d. 1886)\n*[[1824]] &ndash; [[Theodor von Heuglin]], German explorer and ornithologist (d. 1876)\n*[[1828]] &ndash; [[Henrik Ibsen]], Norwegian poet, playwright, and director (d. 1906)\n*[[1831]] &ndash; [[Patrick Jennings]], Northern Irish-Australian politician, 11th [[Premier of New South Wales]] (d. 1897)\n*  1831   &ndash; [[Solomon L. Spink]], American lawyer and politician (d. 1881)\n*[[1834]] &ndash; [[Charles William Eliot]], American mathematician and academic (d. 1926)\n*[[1836]] &ndash; [[Ferris Jacobs, Jr.]], American general, lawyer, and politician (d. 1886)\n*  1836   &ndash; [[Edward Poynter]], English painter, illustrator, and curator (d. 1919)\n*[[1840]] &ndash; [[Illarion Pryanishnikov]], Russian painter (d. 1894)\n*[[1851]] &ndash; [[Ismail Gasprinski]], Ukrainian educator, publisher, and politician (d. 1914)\n*[[1856]] &ndash; [[John Lavery]], Irish painter (d. 1941)\n*  1856   &ndash; [[Frederick Winslow Taylor]], American tennis player and engineer (d. 1915)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck]], German general (d. 1964)<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck {{!}} German officer |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Paul-von-Lettow-Vorbeck |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[B\u00f6rries von M\u00fcnchhausen]], German poet and activist (d. 1945)\n*[[1876]] &ndash; [[Payne Whitney]], American businessman and philanthropist (d. 1927)\n*[[1879]] &ndash; [[Maud Menten]], Canadian physician and biochemist (d. 1960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Maud-Leonora-Menten|title=Maud Leonora Menten {{!}} Canadian biochemist and organic chemist|last=Rogers|first=Kara|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n*[[1882]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 Coty]], French lawyer and politician, 17th [[President of France]] (d. 1962)\n*  1882   &ndash; [[Harold Weber]], American golfer (d. 1933)\n*[[1884]] &ndash; [[Philipp Frank]], Austrian-American physicist, mathematician, and philosopher (d. 1966)\n*  1884   &ndash; [[John Jensen (public servant)|John Jensen]], Australian public servant (d. 1970)\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Vernon Ransford]], Australian cricketer (d. 1958)\n*[[1888]] &ndash; [[Amanda Clement]], American baseball player, umpire, and educator (d. 1971)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Lauritz Melchior]], Danish-American tenor and actor (d. 1973)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Amalie Sara Colquhoun]], Australian landscape and portrait painter (d. 1974)\n*[[1895]] &ndash; [[Fredric Wertham]], German-American psychologist and author (d. 1981)\n*[[1898]] &ndash; [[Eduard Wiiralt]], Estonian artist (d. 1954) \n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Amelia Chopitea Villa]], Bolivia's first female physician (d. 1942)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sucre-historica.blogspot.ca/2016/11/chopitea-villa-maria-amelia-1900-1951.html |title=CHOPITEA VILLA MAR\u00cdA AMELIA (1900 - 1951) |website=sucre-historica.blogspot.ca |access-date=2017-10-19 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Edgar Buchanan]], American actor (d. 1979)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[B. F. Skinner]], American psychologist and author (d. 1990)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Jean Galia]], French rugby player and boxer (d. 1949)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Abraham Beame]], American accountant and politician, 104th [[Mayor of New York City]] (d. 2001)\n*  1906   &ndash; [[Ozzie Nelson]], American actor and bandleader (d. 1975)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Hugh MacLennan]], Canadian author and educator (d. 1990)\n*[[1908]] &ndash; [[Michael Redgrave]], English actor and director (d. 1985)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Erwin Blask]], German hammer thrower (d. 1999)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Alfonso Garc\u00eda Robles]], Mexican lawyer and diplomat, [[Nobel Peace Prize|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1991)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Ralph Hauenstein]], American businessman and philanthropist (d. 2016)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Nikolai Stepulov]], Russian-Estonian boxer (d. 1968)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Wendell Corey]], American actor and politician (d. 1968)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Rudolf Kirchschl\u00e4ger]], Austrian judge and politician, 8th [[President of Austria]] (d. 2000)\n*  1915   &ndash; [[Sviatoslav Richter]], Ukrainian pianist and composer (d. 1997)\n*  1915   &ndash; [[Sister Rosetta Tharpe]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 1973)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Pierre Messmer]], French lieutenant and politician, [[Prime Minister of France]] (d. 2007)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Vera Lynn]], English singer, songwriter and actress\n*  1917   &ndash; [[Yigael Yadin]], Israeli archaeologist, general, and politician, [[Deputy leaders of Israel|Deputy Prime Minister of Israel]] (d. 1984)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Jack Barry (game show host)|Jack Barry]], American game show host and producer, co-founded [[Barry & Enright Productions]] (d. 1984)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Donald Featherstone (wargamer)|Donald Featherstone]], English soldier and author (d. 2013)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Marian McPartland]], English-American pianist and composer (d. 2013)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Bernd Alois Zimmermann]], German composer (d. 1970)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Gerhard Barkhorn]], [[Germany|German]] fighter ace (d. 1983)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Pamela Harriman]], English-American diplomat, 58th [[United States Ambassador to France]] (d. 1997)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Rosemary Timperley]], English author and screenwriter (d. 1988)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Usmar Ismail]], Indonesian filmmaker (d. 1971)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Du\u0161an Pirjevec]], Slovenian historian and philosopher (d. 1977)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Alfr\u00e9d R\u00e9nyi]], Hungarian mathematician and theorist (d. 1970)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Larry Elgart]], American saxophonist and bandleader (d. 2017)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Ray Goulding]], American actor and screenwriter (d. 1990)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Carl Reiner]], American actor, director, producer, and screenwriter\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Con Martin]], Irish footballer and manager (d. 2013)\n*  1923   &ndash; [[Shaukat Siddiqui]], Pakistani journalist, author, and activist (d. 2006)\n*[[1925]] &ndash; [[John Ehrlichman]], American lawyer, 12th [[White House Counsel]] (d. 1999)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[John Joubert (composer)|John Joubert]], South African-English composer and academic (d. 2019)\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Jerome Biffle]], American long jumper and coach (d. 2002)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[James P. Gordon]], American physicist and engineer (d. 2013)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[Fred Rogers]], American television host and producer (d. 2003)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[William Andrew MacKay]], Canadian lawyer and judge (d. 2013)\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Germ\u00e1n Robles]], Spanish-Mexican actor and director (d. 2015)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[S. Arasaratnam]], Sri Lankan historian, author, and academic (d. 1998)\n*[[1931]] &ndash; [[Hal Linden]], American actor, singer, and director\n*  1931   &ndash; [[Rein Raamat]], Estonian director and screenwriter\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Lateef Adegbite]], Nigerian lawyer and politician (d. 2012)\n*  1933   &ndash; [[George Altman]], American baseball player\n*  1933   &ndash; [[Ian Walsh (rugby league)|Ian Walsh]], Australian rugby league player and coach (d. 2013)\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Willie Brown (politician)|Willie Brown]], American soldier, lawyer, and politician, 41st [[Mayor of San Francisco]]\n*  1934   &ndash; [[David Malouf]], Australian author and playwright\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Ted Bessell]], American actor and director (d. 1996)\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Bettye Washington Greene]], American chemist (d. 1995)\n*[[1936]] &ndash; [[Lee \"Scratch\" Perry]], Jamaican singer, songwriter, music producer, and inventor\n*  1936   &ndash; [[Mark Saville, Baron Saville of Newdigate]], English lieutenant, lawyer, and judge\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Lois Lowry]], American author\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Jerry Reed]], American singer-songwriter, guitarist, and actor (d. 2008)\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Sergei Novikov (mathematician)|Sergei Novikov]], Russian mathematician and academic\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Gerald Curran]], American lawyer and politician (d. 2013)\n*  1939   &ndash; [[Don Edwards (cowboy singer)|Don Edwards]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist\n*  1939   &ndash; [[Walter Jakob Gehring]], Swiss biologist and academic (d. 2014)\n*  1939   &ndash; [[Brian Mulroney]], Canadian lawyer and politician, 18th [[Prime Minister of Canada]]\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Stathis Chaitas]], Greek footballer and manager\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Mary Ellen Mark]], American photographer and journalist (d. 2015)\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Giampiero Moretti]], Italian race car driver and businessman, founded the [[Momo (company)|Momo company]] (d. 2012)\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Pat Corrales]], American baseball player and manager\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Kenji Kimihara]], Japanese runner\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Gerard Malanga]], American poet and photographer\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Douglas Tompkins]], American businessman, co-founded [[The North Face]] and [[Esprit Holdings]] (d. 2015)\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Paul Junger Witt]], American director and producer (d. 2018)\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[John Cameron (musician)|John Cameron]], English composer and conductor\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Camille Cosby]], American author, producer, and philanthropist\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Alan Harper (bishop)|Alan Harper]], English-Irish archbishop\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Henry Bartholomay]], American soldier and pilot (d. 2015)\n*  1945   &ndash; [[Jay Ingram]], Canadian television host and author\n*  1945   &ndash; [[Pat Riley]], American basketball player and coach\n*  1945   &ndash; [[Tim Yeo]], English politician, [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Douglas B. Green]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist \n*  1946   &ndash; [[Malcolm Simmons]], English motorcycle racer (d. 2014)\n*[[1947]] &ndash; [[John Boswell]], American historian, philologist, and academic (d. 1994)\n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[John de Lancie]], American actor\n*  1948   &ndash; [[Bobby Orr]], Canadian ice hockey player and coach\n*  1948   &ndash; [[Nikos Papazoglou]], Greek singer-songwriter and producer (d. 2011)\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Marcia Ball]], American blues singer-songwriter and pianist\n*  1949   &ndash; [[Richard Dowden]], English journalist and educator\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[William Hurt]], American actor\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Carl Palmer]], English drummer, percussionist, and songwriter\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Jimmie Vaughan]], American blues-rock singer-songwriter and guitarist\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Geoff Brabham]], Australian race car driver\n*  1952   &ndash; [[David Greenaway (economist)|David Greenaway]], English economist and academic\n*[[1953]] &ndash; [[Phil Judd]], New Zealand singer-songwriter, guitarist and painter \n*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Mike Francesa]], American radio talk show host and television commentator\n*  1954   &ndash; [[Liana Kanelli]], Greek journalist and politi